Every Spark job starts the same way, by reading data in. So let's look at the read side properly, the input sources you can pull from, and the knobs on spark dot read that control how that reading happens.

First, the sources. Spark can read an enormous range of formats and systems through one consistent interface. CSV, the messy text format you'll fight with most. Parquet, the columnar format you should prefer, because it's compressed, typed, and lets Spark skip columns it doesn't need. JSON for nested, semi-structured data. ORC, another columnar format common in the Hive world. JDBC for pulling straight from a relational database. Hive tables from a metastore. Plain files on a filesystem or object store. And Delta, which adds transactions and time travel on top of Parquet. The point is, the same spark dot read call handles all of them, you just change the format.

Now the four sets of knobs that shape a read. The first is format options, which mostly matter for text formats. Header tells Spark the first row of a CSV is column names, not data. Sep sets the separator, a comma, a tab, a pipe, whatever your file uses. Merge schema, for Parquet, combines schemas across files when columns differ between them. And multi line lets a single JSON record or CSV field span several lines instead of assuming one record per line.

The second set is the one people skip and then regret, bad record handling, set through the mode option. Real data has broken rows, and you get to decide what happens. Permissive is the default. It keeps going, sets the broken fields to null, and stashes the raw broken text in a special corrupt record column. Fail fast is the opposite. The first bad row throws an error and stops the job, which is what you want when correctness matters more than completeness. Drop malformed just silently discards bad rows. Column name of corrupt record lets you rename that special column that holds the salvaged garbage. And bad records path tells Spark to write the rejected rows out to a folder, so you can inspect them later instead of losing them. Choosing this deliberately is the difference between trusting your data and being silently lied to.

The third set is multi-file lookup, for when one read needs to pull in many files at once. Glob patterns let you use wildcards in the path, like star dot parquet, to match a whole set of files. Regex gives you finer matching. You can also pass multiple explicit paths in one call. And recursive file lookup tells Spark to dive into nested subfolders instead of only reading the top level directory. This is how you read a whole partitioned dataset in a single line.

The fourth set is special, and it's the one that separates a fast database read from a painfully slow one, JDBC parallel reads. By default, when Spark reads from a database, it opens a single connection and pulls the entire table through one thread. One executor doing all the work while the rest sit idle. To fix that, you tell Spark how to split the table. Partition column names a numeric or date column to divide on. Lower bound and upper bound give the range of values in that column. And num partitions says how many chunks, and therefore how many parallel connections, to use. Spark then slices the range into that many pieces and reads them all at once. There's also fetch size, which tunes how many rows each connection pulls per round trip. Set these four together and a slow database extract suddenly runs in parallel across your whole cluster.

So when you read, picture it in two lanes. On one side, parsing and validation, the format options and the bad-record mode that decide how raw bytes become clean rows. On the other side, what to read and how fast, multi-file lookup for picking files and JDBC parallel reads for splitting a database table. Get these right at the front door and the rest of your pipeline starts on solid ground. Reach for Parquet over CSV when you can, always decide your bad-record mode on purpose, and never read a big table over JDBC single-threaded.
